@Node "intro" "Introduction"

@{b}What is MidiTracker?@{ub}

MidiTracker is a midi sequencer that uses the 'tracker' concept for
composing songs, hence the name. :-) Unlike other tracker programs that
have midi capabilities, MidiTracker has been designed specifically for midi
composing and doesn't use any amiga audio (except for the metronome). If
you have used trackers before, then it shouldn't take you too long to get
accustomed to MidiTracker. Check out the @{" basic differences " link "tracker_differences"} between 
MidiTracker and other trackers.

The intention with MidiTracker is to keep everything as dynamic as possible
thus giving you more freedom and control over your midi data within a
tracker environment. For example, have you ever had the problem of wanting
to realtime record pitchbend, modulation, aftertouch and sustains but the
tracker either didn't get the notes properly or wasn't capable of doing so?
MidiTracker can do it.

Check out some of MidiTracker's other @{" features " link "features"}.

@Endnode
@Node "tracker_differences" "For the Tracker aware..."

@{u}For the Tracker Freaks@{uu}

There are a few fundamental differences between MidiTracker and other
trackers you may have used before.

1. You have additional midi control data tracks that parallel the note
   event tracks. 

2. You have one BPM track per pattern that is visible when viewing any 
   of the instruments.

3. To allow more simultaneous note events per pattern, MidiTracker has
   divided the pattern into 16 separate pages, one for each instrument.
   This enables easier management of each instrument's part and gives you
   unlimited tracks to play with. One drawback of this layout is knowing
   where note events occur on other instruments at the current position. 
   The @{" ChannelScope " link "cscope"} enables  you to see at a glance what other 
   instruments contain midi data and the numeric keypad is configured for
   fast instrument selection, so you can switch between them to view other 
   parts of your current pattern. Check out a more detailed description of 
   MidiTracker's internal @{" structure " link "understanding"}.

4. MidiTracker allows you to zoom in and out of a pattern by adjusting the
   @{" resolution " link "resolution-example"} enabling fine adjustment of note timings at high resolution 
   and the ability to see more events on screen at once at a low resolution.

   
@Endnode
@Node "legal" "Legal information"

@{u}Shareware@{uu}

MidiTracker is shareware which means you may use this version for
assessment purposes only. If you wish to be a regular user of MidiTracker
and have the shareware @{" limitations " link "Limit"} removed via personal keyfile,
you must @{" register " link "register"} and help support future development of MidiTracker.

Registered users are eligible to receive regular version updates, and
support for their synth's SYSEX implementation (click @{" here " link "synths"} for
details.)

