@Node "megaline" "Spacerbar, the keeper of the peace.."

Yep it's the Spacerbar!!!  It's his duty to keep hostile menu options from
kicking each other in the vowels. :-)

@Endnode
@Node "damn" "Alignment'R'Use"

I needed that little thingy to keep everything aligned properly, it's of
no real consequence. Sorry if it has caused you any anguish.

@Endnode
@Node "clearsong" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Clear song@{uu}

Will erase the current song from memory. If the current song has changed
since the last save, you will be asked for confirmation before flushing the
song.

@Endnode
@Node "opensong" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Open Song File@{uu}

This is the universal song loader for MidiTracker. The following types of
files are currently supported:

* MidiTracker songfiles
* Protracker modules, 15/31 voices (The first 16 instruments are taken.)
* Octamed modules (MMD1) 
* Standard Midi Files (Type 1)

The @{" XPK-compressors " link "compressor"} are supported on all file types.

See the @{" Future plans " link "todo"} for a list of module/song formats I may support 
in new versions of MidiTracker.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + o

@Endnode
@Node "openquick" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Open quick@{uu}

The recent five loaded or saved songs are here. The most recent one has
a hotkey attached to it.

@Endnode
@Node "savesong" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Save song@{uu}

Saves the current song using its @{" song name " link "songname"} with a '.mt' appended 
to the end of it. If you haven't named the song then a 'save as' requester
will be displayed.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + w

@Endnode
@Node "savesongas" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Save song as@{uu}

Save song to a filename of your choice.

* Please note that if you enter a save file name in the requester that your
file will NOT have a '.mt' automatically appended to it, you must type it in.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + W

@Endnode
@Node "exportmid" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Export SMF File@{uu}

Save as a Type-1 multitrack Standard MIDI file.

@Endnode
@Node "songname" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Songname@{uu}

Allows you to enter the name of the current song. If you use @{" Save " link "savesong"}
from the menu, MidiTracker will use this name with a '.mt' appended to the
end as the file name.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + N

@Endnode
@Node "songauthor" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Author@{uu}

This is where you may enter your name. If you are a registered user your
name will be the default author.

@Endnode
@Node "about" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}About MidiTracker@{uu}

The usual credits and information.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + ?

@Endnode
@Node "onlinehelp" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Online Help@{uu} (Kick 3.0+ only) 

When enabled a small window will display helpful information about the
gadget under the current mouse position. Move the mouse around the screen
to get more information on other buttons and gadgets.

@Endnode
@Node "iconify" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Iconify@{uu}

This will hide MidiTracker in the background using the hide method in the
@{" System Preferences " link "sysprefs"}. Songs will continue to play while iconified.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + h

@Endnode
@Node "kick" "MAIN SCREEN - PROJECT MENU"

@{u}Kick@{uu}

Quit MidiTracker. If your song has changed since the last save, a
requester will pop up and ask for confirmation before quitting.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + q

@Endnode
@Node "jointrack" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Join track@{uu}

This is where the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} is combined with the current track. The 
copy-buffer data may overwrite positions that already contain note data
depending on how you have set the @{" join does overlay " link "joindoesoverlay"} flag.

Please note for track operations edit-mode must be enabled. This is
because MidiTracker selects the current track by the cursor position.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + F2

@Endnode
@Node "copy-buffer" "This is where the data goes..."

When you cut or copy data, this is where it is stored in ram until the next
cut or copy goes over the top of it.

@Endnode
@Node "cuttrack" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Cut track@{uu}

If "copy to buffers" is enabled in the @{" Edit Preferences " link "editprefs"} then the current 
track is copied to the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} and then cut from the pattern.

Please note for track operations edit-mode must be enabled. This is
because MidiTracker selects the current track by the cursor position.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + F3

@Endnode
@Node "copytrack" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Copy track@{uu}

Copy the current track to the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"}.

Please note for track operations edit-mode must be enabled. This is
because MidiTracker selects the current track by the cursor position.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + F4

@Endnode
@Node "pastetrack" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Paste track@{uu}

Paste the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} into the current track. All data in
the destination track is written over by the new data.

Please note for track operations edit-mode must be enabled. This is
because MidiTracker selects the current track by the cursor position.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + F5

@Endnode
@Node "joinchannel" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Join Instrument@{uu}

This is where the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} is combined with the current
instrument. The copy-buffer data may overwrite positions that already
contain note data depending on how you have set the @{" join does overlay " link "joindoesoverlay"} 
flag.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + F2

@Endnode
@Node "cutchannel" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Cut Instrument@{uu}

If "copy to buffers" is enabled in the @{" Edit Preferences " link "editprefs"} then the current 
instrument is copied to the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} and then cut from the pattern.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + F3

@Endnode
@Node "copychannel" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Copy Instrument@{uu}

Copy the current instrument to the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"}.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + F4

@Endnode
@Node "pastechannel" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Paste Instrument@{uu}

Paste the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} into the current instrument. All data in
the destination instrument is written over by the new data.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + F5

@Endnode
@Node "joinpattern" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Join pattern@{uu}

This is where the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} is combined with the current pattern.
The copy-buffer data may overwrite positions that already contain note
data depending on how you have set the @{" join does overlay " link "joindoesoverlay"} flag.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + ALT + F2

@Endnode
@Node "cutpattern" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Cut pattern@{uu}

If "copy to buffers" is enabled in the @{" Edit Preferences " link "editprefs"} then the current 
pattern is copied to the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} and then deleted.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + ALT + F3

@Endnode
@Node "copypattern" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Copy pattern@{uu}

Copy the current pattern to the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"}.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + ALT + F4

@Endnode
@Node "pastepattern" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Paste pattern@{uu}

Paste the @{" copy-buffer " link "copy-buffer"} into the current pattern. All data in
the destination pattern is written over by the new data.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + ALT + F5

@Endnode
@Node "delete2eot" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Delete to End of Track@{uu}

Deletes all events to the end of the track including the event at the current
cursor position. Editmode must be enabled.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + k

@Endnode
@Node "fixvelocity" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Fix Velocity@{uu}

All velocity values of the current track or instrument are changed to a
fixed value. The user is asked to enter a velocity value between 0 and 7F.
(Values are hexadecimal because the trackdisplay shows these values in hex
too.)

Please note for track operations edit-mode must be enabled. This is because
MidiTracker selects the current track by the cursor position. The edit
status is irrelevant for instrument operations.

@{b}HOTKEY (FIX VELOCITY-TRACK):@{ub} R-AMIGA + f

@Endnode
@Node "shiftcontrolsource" "MAIN SCREEN - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Shift Controlsource@{uu}

This function enables you to shift all values in the current controlsource
track (except pitchbend) by a user defined amount. This amount can be a
value from -128 to +128 and only affects the currently selected
controlsource track. 

Example: If you have recorded an expression controller and the overall
level is a bit soft, you may 'shift' or increment all the data in the track
by adding 20 to the controlsource values in the track.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + C

@Endnode
@Node "undolastrecord" "MAIN SCREEN - ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Undo Last Recording@{uu}

This function is used to return the pattern(s) to the state they were
before the last record. This is useful when you recorded a part across
multiple patterns and you don't like the recording. Select Undo and your
last recording is deleted.

@Endnode
@Node "synths" "Special support for some synths"

@{u}Custom support for your synth@{uu}

MidiTracker has SysEx support for various synths. For each synth there is
a dialog window, so you can select any preset (to the current instrument)
just by clicking on its name. In editmode this program change is put into
the current preset track.

If the menuitem @{u}Use entries as instrument-name@{uu} is checked, the name
of the entry you clicked is used as the @{" instrument's name " link "channame"} .

Please note it may take some time to read all preset data via midi from
your synth.

Depending on the synth, there may be more features other than just preset
selection. The following synths are supported:

  @{" Kurzweil K2000 " link "k2k"}
  @{" Alesis Quadrasynth " link "quadra"}
  @{" Boehm Dynamic 12/24 " link "boehm"}
  @{" Roland MC-303" link "mc303"}
  @{" Yamaha XG" link "yamahaxg"}
  @{" Yamaha CS1x" link "cs1x"}
  @{" Quasimidi Quasar" link "quasar"}

Ok it isn't much yet, but *YOU* can make this list grow!

If you would like a dialog window for your synth, @{" send me " link "author"} the synth's 
SysEx implementation documentation and the next MidiTracker release should
have a dialog window for your synth. I will only be implementing SysEx
code for registered users, as it does take time and effort to code the
custom dialog windows.

@Endnode
@Node "progchangetype" "Program change type"

@{u}Program Changes@{uu}

Choose the method of sending program changes for each instrument by
clicking the corresponding listview entry. A single selection window
will pop up so you can choose the method you require.


@{i}Extended@{ui}

  MIDI Controller 32 is used to send the bank (the hundred's digit,) and
  then the ProgChange Command sends the preset number (decimal) for that
  instrument. (EG. This is used in the K2000 and 01/W synths.)

  Example: hexdump B0 20 02 C0 29
  bank 2 program 29(hex)=41(dec) -> select preset 241 on instrument 1.


@{i}Normal (GM)@{ui}

  This is used by General-MIDI devices with only preset numbers 0-127
  recognized. 


@{i}JV1080 banks@{ui}

  These are special to the Roland JV1080 synth.


The other program change types are specific to the supported synths.

@Endnode
@Node "quantizerec" "MAIN SCREEN"

@{u}Quantize Record@{uu}

If selected all incoming notes are quantized to the @{" Resolution " link "resolution"} value 
set on the main screen. No notes will be recorded between two displayed 
events.

If not selected, none of the incoming notes will be quantized. This is useful
when recording a live solo or a sequence from another sequencer and you
want MidiTracker to record at its highest resolution to get all the timing 
right.

Note that quantize recording does not quantize midi controlsources, which
are ALWAYS recorded at the highest resolution. See an @{"example " link "resolution-example"}.

@Endnode
@Node "recmode" "MAIN SCREEN"

@{u}Record Mode@{uu}

There are three different methods to record into a pattern or song. The
following modes are available:

@{u}Standard@{uu}

When you hit @{" record pattern " link "recpatt"} or @{" record song " link "recsong"} MidiTracker will start 
recording immediately. If you have the @{" metronome " link "metroenable"} enabled, you will get 
a count in before the pattern starts to play.

@{u}Auto-MIDI@{uu}

When you hit record a requester will be displayed saying 'Automatic
recording active, waiting for input...' MidiTracker starts recording as
soon as it receives the first midi event from your keyboard (except for
SysEx messages.) If you do not wish to record yet, you may hit cancel.

If the metronome is enabled it will start playing as soon as you do, without
the count in bars.

@{u}Audition@{uu}

The current pattern is played through once and on the second pass record
mode is activated and you are able to record note events. You can adjust
the number of playback passes in @{" MIDI Preferences / Audition passes " link "audpasses"}.

Audition mode only functions with pattern record.

@Endnode
@Node "screenmode" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Screen mode@{uu}

Select a new screenmode for MidiTracker.

@Endnode
@Node "realtimetrackdisplay" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Realtime Trackdisplay@{uu}

If this feature is enabled, the current instrument is scrolled in playback
or record mode (default.) If disabled, only the event position counter will
change. You should use this feature to reduce CPU load if you have a slow
Amiga.

@Endnode
@Node "loadprefs" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Load prefs@{uu}

A file requester is displayed allowing you to choose a prefs file to load.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + l

@Endnode
@Node "saveprefs" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Save prefs@{uu}

Save preferences to "MidiTracker.prefs" or the name you supplied in the 
@{" tooltypes or shell arguments " link "start"}.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + s

@Endnode
@Node "saveprefsas" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Save prefs as@{uu}

A file requester is displayed allowing you to enter a name to save the
prefs as.

@Endnode
@Node "marktrack" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Mark track@{uu}

Mark track is used if you only want to copy a section of track. Use the
cursor to highlight the note events you want to cut/copy. The start and
end positions of your marked block are shown in @{" main window's title " link "maintitle"}.

Editmode must be enabled.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + b

@Endnode
@Node "markchannel" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Mark instrument@{uu}

Mark instrument functions the same way as @{" mark track " link "marktrack"} except that
it highlights all note, BPM, preset and controlsource tracks within the
pattern for that instrument.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + B

@Endnode
@Node "cutblock" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Cut block@{uu}

Cut block deletes the highlighted block AND drags up all note events below
the block up to the start position of the marked block. If @{" cut to buffers " link "cuttobuffers"} 
is enabled, the block is copied into the block copy buffer before being
deleted.

If you do not wish notes to be dragged up after a cut use @{" clear block " link "clearblock"}. 

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + x

@Endnode
@Node "clearblock" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Clear block@{uu}

All highlighted note events are deleted and the events below that remain
where they are.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + n

@Endnode
@Node "copyblock" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Copy block@{uu}

Copies the block to block copy buffer. Please note that for BPM, Preset,
Pitchbend and other tracks use different copy buffers. This means, you
cannot copy a BPM track into a Preset track.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + c

@Endnode
@Node "spreadblock" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Spread block@{uu}

This useful function enables you to spread values within the highlighted
range. For example if you wanted to increase the modulation of an
instrument slightly, you would do the following :

1) Set the SRC track to ModW
2) At POS 001 enter 10 
3) At POS 004 enter 20 
4) Mark the block from 001 to 004
5) Now spread block.

  before: [ModW]     after: [ModW]
            00                00
000       B 10                10
001       B 00                14
002       B 00                18
003       B 00                1C
004       B 20                20
005         00                00

("B" is showing the marked block)

All events residing between the start and end values are evenly spread. You can
see the result in the @{" Controlsource graphical display " link "csources"}.

If the cursor is in a normal track (with notes in it,) a requester will be
displayed asking if you wish to spread velocity or poly pressure.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + d

@Endnode
@Node "randomizer" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Randomizer@{uu}

The randomizer is used to randomize (go figure ;-) velocities and Poly
Pressure values. Highlight a block of note events with @{" Mark track " link "marktrack"} then 
select the the randomizer function to process the block.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + r

@Endnode
@Node "flipblock"  "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Flip Block@{uu}

The marked block will be rotated. Example:

  before: [ModW]     after: [ModW]
            00                00
000       B 10                50
001       B 20                40
002       B 30                30
003       B 40                20
004       B 50                10
005         00                00

@Endnode
@Node "invertblock"  "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Invert Block@{uu}

All values in the marked block will be inverted, i.e. mirrored to the
value 64. Example:

  before: [ModW]     after: [ModW]
            00                00
000       B 20                60
001       B 30                50
002       B 40                40
003       B 30                50
004       B 20                60
005         00                00

@Endnode
@Node "shiftblock"  "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Shift Block@{uu}

You are prompted for a value which is then added to values within the
marked block. Negative values are also allowed. This is similar to
the shift Shift controlsource `shiftcontrolsource` function. 

@Endnode
@Node "pastemode" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Paste mode@{uu}

You have two options overwrite or insert. Overwrite mode means that the
pasted block will be kill any existing notes underneath it. Insert Mode
will shuffle down the existing notes and paste the block in their previous
position. This setting affects @{" paste track " link "pastetrackblock"} and 
@{" paste instrument " link "pasteblockchannel"}.

@Endnode
@Node "pasteblocktrack" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Paste track@{uu}

Paste the block copy buffer into the track according to the cursor's
position. Editmode must be enabled.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + v

@Endnode
@Node "pasteblockchannel" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Paste instrument@{uu}

Paste the block copy buffer into the current instrument according to the
cursor's position.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + V

@Endnode
@Node "joinblocktrack" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Join track@{uu}

Join track will merge the block copy buffer into the destination track.
The @{" Join does overlay " link "editprefs"} setting decides what to do if there is note 
being pasted over an existing note.

Editmode must be enabled.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + y

@Endnode
@Node "joinblockchannel" "MAIN SCREEN - BLOCK MENU"

@{u}Join instrument@{uu}

Join instrument will merge the block copy buffer into the destination
instrument. The @{" Join does overlay " link "editprefs"} setting decides what to do if 
there's a note being pasted over an existing note.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + Y

@Endnode
@Node "mainwindow" "This is where most the action takes place..."

@{u}The Main Display@{uu}

@{"   Menus  " link "mainmenus"}@{"                         Titlebar                           " link "maintitle"} 

 @{" |< " link "fastrewind"} @{" [] " link "stopbutton"} @{" >  " link "playpatt"} @{" |> " link "playsong"} @{" >> " link "forward"} @{" >| " link "fastforward"} @{" O  " link "recpatt"} @{" |O " link "recsong"} @{" Transpose " link "transpose"}  @{" Song   " link "subsong"}@{"" link ""}    @{"" link ""}
 @{" Ignore NOffs   " link "ignorenoteoffs"}       @{" Record mode       " link "recmode"}              @{" Length " link "songlength"}@{"" link ""}    @{"" link ""}
 @{" Metronome      " link "metroenable"}       @{" Quantize Record   " link "quantizerec"}              @{" Patt   " link "pattern"}@{"" link ""}    @{"" link ""}
