 @{" SMPTE " link "timegadget"} 00:00:00:00 @{" Src " link "srcgadget"}         @{"Vel/PP" link "velorpp"}             @{" Loop Song " link "loopsong"}@{"" link ""}  @{" Position List " link "position"}

 @{"POS" link "posgadget"}@{" BPM  " link "bpmgadget"}@{"Bnk.Pre " link "pregadget"}@{"ModW" link "cntrlgadget"}@{" Track 1 Track 2 Track 3 Track 4 Track 5 Track 6 " link "trackgadget"}
 -------------------------------------------------------------------------
 000 125.00 001.100  00    60C#4   -----   5CF-4   -----   -----   -----
 001 ------ -------  10    -----   -----   -----   -----   -----   -----
 002 ------ -------  20    50OFF   -----   5FG#4   -----   -----   -----
 003 ------ -------  --    -----   -----   -----   -----   -----   -----

SEE ALSO  @{" Structure " link "understanding"}
@Endnode
@Node "maintitle" "Main window's title bar"

@{u}The main window title bar@{uu}

The title bar contains vital information showing MidiTrackers current
state. From left to right the information is as follows :-

* Message showing the current operational status of MidiTracker.

* Five characters to indicate the status of important flags. When there is a 
  '-' the function is disabled. The flags are :-

  I  -  @{" Ignore " link "ignorenoteoffs"} incoming Note-OFFs. @{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + i 

  D  -  Play @{" muted tracks " link "playdisabled"}. All tracks are played, no matter
        if they're muted or not. @{b}HOTKEY:@{ub}  ALT + d 

  S  -  Send @{" sequencer Realtime sysex " link "sendseq"} messages. When active
        MidiTracker will send sequencer start/stop messages on song play and 
        stop. @{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + s 

  H  -  @{" Halt pattern " link "stoppatternsend"} when it has reached its end. This works while 
        @{" playing " link "playing"} or @{" recording " link "recording"} a pattern. @{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + h 

  M  -  Send @{" MIDI Time Code " link "mtc"}. @{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + m 

  K  -  See @{" Keyboard Actions " link "keyboardactions"} in the settings menu for information.

* After the flags the active @{" octave " link "octave"} is displayed. This is for 
  Amiga-keyboard notes only.

* If a @{" block " link "mainmenus"} is marked, the beginning and the end the block
  positions are displayed after the octave. This looks like xxxx-yyyy
  where xxxx and yyyy are the beginning and ending event-numbers 
  respectively.

* Next we have the @{" songname " link "songname"}. If an asterisk is in front of the song 
  name, it means that your song has been changed since the last save.

@Endnode
@Node "insertpos" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Insert position@{uu}

All positions after the current position are shifted down one and a new
position is inserted. The song length is increased by one. 

@Endnode
@Node "deletepos" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Delete position@{uu}

The current position is deleted and lower positions are dragged up one. The
song length is reduced by one.

@Endnode
@Node "position" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Positions List@{uu}

You can use the scrollbar or arrows to navigate through the song's
positions. The total number of positions is limited by the song's length.
The pattern number at the current position can be changed by typing the
value into the input field in the middle of the listview or using the
arrows beside it.

You may use the @{" Insert " link "insertpos"} or @{" Delete " link "deletepos"} buttons to edit the
arrangement accordingly.

@Endnode
@Node "loopsong" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Loop Song@{uu}

If selected and in play song mode, the song will loop back to the position
in box next to the loop song check box. To disable, un-check the box.

Loop Song [ ] 1
               \ 
              If set to one, the song will reach the end and then loop to
              the beginning and will continue until you hit stop. To change
              this value, select the loop position in @{" positions list " link "position"} 
              (ie the current position in the input field) and click on the
              number.

@{b}TIP:@{ub} This is handy if you want to repeat a chorus at the end of a song
many times as it saves you from having to enter the position sequences over
and over.

@Endnode
@Node "velorpp" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Velocity/PPress switch@{uu}

Choose @{b}Vel@{ub} for velocity or @{b}PP@{ub} for poly-pressure to be displayed in the
main window @{" trackdisplay " link "trackgadget"}, next to the note.

@Endnode
@Node "songlength" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Song length@{uu}

The length of the song in positions.

@Endnode
@Node "subsong" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Song number@{uu}

The current song selected.

@Endnode
@Node "pattern" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Current pattern@{uu}

Current pattern which is being displayed in the track display. If you
click on the 'Patt' you activate the Pattern Lock Mode.

@{u}Pattern Lock Mode@{uu}

This will auto-select the pattern that's at the current song position in
edit mode. The pattern entry field is disabled.

@{b}TIP:@{ub} Say you have a song position list and you would like to check the
contents of each pattern.

Patterns
   01
  [10] <- With pattern lock, pattern 10 will be displayed.
   11
   21
   11

Instead of selecting pattern 1, then selecting pattern 10 etc. you may
use pattern lock and the patterns will be selected automatically as you
cycle through the song position list. 

Also be aware that if you change patterns in pattern lock mode, you will be
changing the pattern number at the current song position!

@Endnode
@Node "timegad" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}SMPTE Timer@{uu}

While playing or recording, the elapsed time is here. Timer is in the form
of hh:mm:ss:ff - HOURS:MINUTES:SECONDS:FRAMES ( MidiTracker is using 25
frames per second.)

@Endnode
@Node "channame" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Instrument Name@{uu}

Enter a name for the current instrument (Upto 23 chars.)

@Endnode
@Node "fastrewind" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Fast rewind@{uu}

Jump to previous pattern during replay.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} F1 (During song playback only)

@Endnode
@Node "stopbutton" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Stop button@{uu}

Stop the music in all play and record modes. If a recording is stopped,
all recorded midi data is then inserted into your song.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SPACEBAR

SEE ALSO @{" Record pattern " link "recpatt"} @{" Record song " link "recsong"}
         @{" Stop at pattern's end " link "stoppatternsend"} @{" Auto recording " link "autorec"}

@Endnode
@Node "playpatt" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Play pattern@{uu}

Play current pattern.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} F4

SEE ALSO @{" Play song " link "playsong"} @{" General info on playing " link "playing"}

@Endnode
@Node "playsong" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Play song@{uu}

Play the song from @{" current position " link "position"}.

MidiTracker will trace back the controlsources and tempo changes, searching
backwards from the current position. So the controlsources and the tempo
are set to their most recent value occuring in previous positions.

You might want a controlsource not to be traced back. See the description of
the file @{" Controlsources " link "files"} how to do this.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} F5

SEE ALSO @{" Play pattern " link "playpatt"} @{" General info on playing " link "playing"}

@Endnode
@Node "forward" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Forward@{uu}

If held down during playback, replay will be twice the normal tempo.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} F2 (While in play pattern or play song mode only)

SEE ALSO @{" Fast forward " link "fastforward"} @{" Fast rewind " link "fastrewind"}

@Endnode
@Node "fastforward" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Fast forward@{uu}

Jump to next pattern during replay.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} F3 (During song playback only)

SEE ALSO @{" Forward " link "forward"} @{" Fast rewind " link "fastrewind"}

@Endnode
@Node "recpatt" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Record pattern@{uu}

Start recording into the current pattern. When you hit stop all recorded
midi data is inserted into the pattern.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + F4 

SEE ALSO @{" How to record " link "recording"} @{" Metronome " link "metroenable"}
         @{" Record song " link "recsong"} @{" Record buffersize " link "recbufsize"}
         @{" Record Modes " link "recmode"}

@Endnode
@Node "recsong" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Record song@{uu}

The same as song play, but in record mode. This enables you to record a
part across multiple patterns. When you hit stop all recorded midi data is
inserted into the pattern(s).


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SHIFT + F5

SEE ALSO @{" How to record " link "recording"} @{" Metronome " link "metroenable"}
         @{" Record pattern " link "recpatt"} @{" Record buffersize " link "recbufsize"}
         @{" Record Modes " link "recmode"}

@Endnode
@Node "panic" "MAIN WINDOW + ACTIONS MENU"

@{u}Panic@{uu}

Hitting the panic button will cause MidiTracker to send an "everything off"
midi message. You can configure what @{" Panic method " link "panicmethod"} you wish to use in 
the @{" MIDI Preferences " link "midiprefs"}.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ESCAPE

SEE ALSO @{" Stop with panic " link "stoppanic"}

@Endnode
@Node "editbutton" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Edit mode@{uu}

Used to turn pattern edit off and on for manual data entry. When active, a
cursor will appear somewhere on the track display's center line. Replay
will not be stopped if you use the button gadget on the main screen.

The edit toggle hotkey is same as the @{" Stop button's " link "stopbutton"} hotkey.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} SPACE

SEE ALSO @{" How to edit " link "editing"}

@Endnode
@Node "chord" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Chord mode@{uu}

Single : When in edit mode, the notes will be put into a single track and
         the cursor will move down one position ( or the @{" edit step " link "quantize"} amount 
         if set) each time a note or value is entered.

Chord :	 When in edit mode, MidiTracker will cycle to the next track for
         the next note of the chord. Playing a note will move the cursor to
         the next track.

Please note that when recording MidiTracker always records in chord mode.


SEE ALSO  @{" How to edit " link "editing"}

@Endnode
@Node "mastervol" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Master volume@{uu}

All volumes on all midi channels are affected by this slider. To change the
volume of a single midi channel, use its slider in @{" channelscope " link "cscope"}.

@Endnode
@Node "bpm" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}BPM - overall tempo@{uu}

The desired tempo can be set by either using the slider or entering the BPM
in the value box. The slider will change the value in +1/-1 steps. If you
want a bpm value with decimal places, you must use the keyboard input gadget.

Possible values are from 1-250 BPM. 

@Endnode
@Node "srcgadget" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}The "Src" gadget@{uu}

Click on it to toggle the controlsource track.

@Endnode
@Node "channel" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Instrument slider@{uu}

Used to select the current instrument to edit. Each instrument has its own 
@{"hotkey " link "navigate"} on the numeric keypad.

@Endnode
@Node "pattsize" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Pattern size@{uu}

You may enter the length of the current pattern here. The pattern size has
a direct relationship with the current @{" resolution " link "resolution"}. The available
resolutions will depend on what value you use as your pattern size. For
example the default pattern is :

64 * 6 = 384 (total positions within the pattern)

Now 384 is divisible by 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48, 64, 96, 128,
192, 384. So these are the available resolutions. If you set the pattern
size to 65, you get

65 * 6 = 390

Now 390 is only divisible by 1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 10, 13 and so on. So your
resolution is limited to the factors of your pattern size.

If you stick to incrementing/decrementing the pattern size by the default
@{" delta value " link "pattsizeD"}, you will always have access to the resolutions
of 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 12, 16, 24 and so on.

@Endnode
@Node "quantize" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Edit Step@{uu}

This enables you to set different values to 'step' when editing in data.
Try editing with different values to see the result.

Please note that edit step is non-destructive and will not delete notes it
'jumps' over.


SEE ALSO @{" How to edit " link "editing"}

@Endnode
@Node "octave" "Amiga Octave"

@{u}Octave@{uu}

This value is the current octave when editing with your Amiga keyboard.
The upper octave row on your keyboard is used for the active octave.

Possible values are 1-9.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} 0 (Numeric Keypad) - 1 Octave Down
@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} . (Numeric Keypad) - 1 Octave Up

SEE ALSO @{" How to edit " link "editing"} @{" Playing notes with your Amiga-keyboard " link "keyboard"}

@Endnode
@Node "solo" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Solo Instrument@{uu}

Switch the current instrument into solo mode. All other instruments are
temporarily set to a volume of 0. This is also shown in @{" channelscope " link "cscope"} 
window.

If solo mode is enabled and you select another instrument, the new
instrument will now solo and the previous instrument is muted like the
rest.

SEE ALSO  @{" Chocolate bar in channelscope " link "chocolatebar"}

@Endnode
@Node "metroenable" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Enable metronome@{uu}

Enable/disable metronome clicking during recording.


SEE ALSO @{" Metronome prefs " link "metro"} @{" How to record " link "recording"}

@Endnode
@Node "autorewind" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Automatic rewind@{uu}

When you @{" stop " link "stopbutton"} a song playing back, MidiTracker jumps back to
the position where you started playing the song from so you don't have to
scroll back manually.

@Endnode
@Node "transpose" "MAIN WINDOW"

@{u}Transpose modes@{uu}

Transposing shifts all Note-ON events a note/octave up or down ( Note-OFF
events are ignored of course.) Please note that you can transpose during
replay (except block and track transpose.)


          Track : Transpose current track only. Editmode must be enabled to
                  determine which track to transpose by the cursor position.

     Instrument : Current instrument of the pattern is transposed.

        Pattern : Current pattern is transposed, all instruments.

           Song : Current song is transposed, all instruments.

Song-Instrument : Current instrument is transposed for the whole song.

          Block : Marked block is transposed.

Use the Oct+,Oct-,Note+,Note- gadgets to transpose the note events.

@Endnode
@Node "posgadget" "TRACK DISPLAY"

A running (decimal) number of the event-position. The blue values are the
positions that F6 - F10 are defined as. If you have @{" Highlight Resolution " link "hiliteres"}
selected in the @{" Edit Preferences " link "editprefs"} then the start resolution values 
will be coloured in white.

See @{" Resolution-example " link "resolution-example"} for more info.

@Endnode
@Node "bpmgadget" "TRACK DISPLAY"

The (decimal) speed in beats-per-minute (Germans:  Metzlers Metronom.) For
PT-freaks: BPM 200 in MidiTracker is speed-effect FC8 in PT.

@Endnode
@Node "pregadget" "TRACK DISPLAY"

@{u}Bank and Preset@{uu}

These (decimal) values are transmitted as bank/program changes to your
synth. The type of program change is defined in the @{" Prog change type " link "progchangetype"}. 

The first number is the bank (0-127), and the second number is the program change
(also 0-127).

@Endnode
@Node "cntrlgadget" "TRACK DISPLAY"

This track contains (hexadecimal) values for the current controlsource.
You can scroll through controlsources by pressing ctrl-cursor-up/down,
pressing the 'SRC" button or selecting them in the @{"controlsources " link "csources"} window.

Pitchbender is the only controlsource with four digits. Values from 0 to
3FFF are possible with the pitchbender's center being 2000. All other
parameters are from 0 - 7F. A value of -- or ---- does nothing and lets the
previous value stay active.

By clicking on the controlsource gadget (Under the SRC button) you can
disabled (mute) the controlsource track. The different colours represent:

  White  =  Track contains some data, and is enabled.
  Black  =  Track is empty and can't be disabled.
  Blue   =  Track is disabled and contains data. 


@Endnode
@Node "trackgadget" "TRACK DISPLAY"

Only six tracks can be displayed on the screen at once. Use the scroller
above (or cursor-right/left in non-editmode) to scroll through the tracks.
You can adjust the number of tracks on @{" startup " link "start"}.

A track entry consists of seven digits: VVNNNPP.
                                        // \|/ \\      
                                       //   |   \\     
                                                       
                                 Velocity  Note  Polypressure

* Velocity VV (hex) values have a range of 00-7F. -- means no change.

* Notes NNN have a range of C-0 to B-9 with a note off being shown as 'OFF'

* A note without a velocity value is played at the same velocity of the
  previous note.

* Polypressure PP (hex) values have a range of 00-7F. Not all midi
  keyboards support Poly Pressure, so check your synth's midi
  implementation chart to see if it can (The ENSONIQ ASR10 transmits and
  receives Poly Pressure.) Some synths can receive PP via midi but they
  can't transmit it (e.g. the K2000 or the Quadrasynth) so you may edit in
  PP values manually if your synth supports it.

* By clicking on these track-gadgets, the corresponding track can be
  muted. Here's an explanation of the colour settings:

  White  =  Track contains some data somewhere, and is enabled.
  Black  =  Track is empty and can't be disabled.
  Blue   =  Track is disabled and contains some data. 

* Also at the top left of the track display the current pattern number is
  shown yet again as a quick reference.

@Endnode
@Node "understanding" "Tracks, instruments, patterns - oh my god!"

@{u}The Structure of Magic@{uu}

This chapter is about the structures used in MidiTracker, their hierarchy,
and how they are managed.

@{u}Song@{uu}

At the top level you have the song. MidiTracker can hold as many songs as
available memory allows. A song consists of a number of positions with each
position pointing to a pattern. Positions represent the arrangement of your
song. Here's a little example.

			PLAY ==>>

Positions:   1  ->  2  ->  3  ->  4  ->  5  ->  ...

             |      |      |      |      |      |
             v      v      v      v      v      v

Patterns:    1      2      1      3      3


Pattern 1 is played at positions 1 and 3, pattern 2 is played at position
2, pattern 3 at position 4 and 5, and so on. Arrange your song in this way,
by using the @{" Position Arrangement " link "position"} at the top right of the main window.

@{u}Patterns@{uu}

A pattern consists of all 16 instruments, and a single BPM-track. The
BPM-track holds tempo changes and is shown in the track display on the Main
Window and you can edit it like any other track.

Only one instrument at a time is shown in trackdisplay. To switch to another
instrument, you may use the @{" instrument " link "channel"} gadget in @{" main-window " link "mainwindow"} or use the
numeric keypad to auto select the instrument. Switching instruments does
not change the BPM-track because there is only one BPM-track per pattern.

@{u}Instrument@{uu} 

An instrument consists of:

  @{i}Preset-track@{ui}
    The preset-track holds all program changes for this instrument. The
    numbers are decimal, from 1 to 999.

  @{i}Controlsource-tracks@{ui}
    The controlsource tracks hold midi-controlsource values. MidiTracker
    supports all 127 midi controlsources, with the more common ones already
    named for convenience :-

      Non-parameter controlsources:  Pitchbend
      [they have their own status]   MonoPressure

      Parameter controlsources:      ( 1) Modwheel
      [technical note: these are     ( 2) Breath-Controller
       sent with $Bn pp vv where     ( 4) Foot Pedal
       n  = MIDI channel             ( 5) PortaTime
       pp = Parameter (the number    ( 6) Data Entry
                       in brackets)  ( 7) Volume
       vv = value ]                  ( 8) Balance
                                     (10) Pan
                                     (11) Express
                                     (64) Sustain
                                     (65) PortSwitch
                                     (66) SostSwitch
                                     (67) SoftPedal
                                     (75) LegaSwitch
                                     (91) FX Depth

    All controlsources are 1-byte-controllers except Pitchbend. 

    You may select any of the 127 control sources using the add controlsrc
    function in the @{" Controlsource Graphical Display " link "csources"}.

  @{i}Note-tracks@{ui}

    Note-tracks hold notes events, attack-velocities and poly-pressures. An
    instrument can hold unlimited note-tracks. The number of total tracks
    per instrument is adjusted in @{" Edit Preferences " link "editprefs"} (Maximum
    Tracks). If notes are entered without velocities, they're played at the
    velocity of the previous note.

@{u}Events@{uu}

MidiTracker uses the word "event" with the following meaning:

An event is a single MIDI-message, for example a Note-ON event, Note-OFF,
program change, parameter change (e.g. set the modwheel to any value,)
etc..

Each pattern has a certain number of events (64 events by default.) In 
the track display, event-numbers are shown on the left. Please note that
unless you have set the @{" resolution " link "resolution"} to ONE, there are hidden events 
between the ones you see. Because you don't want to edit at the highest
resolution (the patterns would be huge,) MidiTracker doesn't show the
'between' events unless you zoom in with the resolution gadget.

SEE ALSO  @{" Edit tracks manually " link "editbutton"}  
          @{" Pattern Resolution " link "resolution"}

@Endnode
@Node "resolution" "Resolution"

@{u}Pattern Resolution@{uu}

This gadget controls the resolution of the current instrument. Its value
will be remembered for each instrument, so if you leave the current
instrument and return to it later, the resolution value is restored.

The @{i}resolution@{ui} value can be compared in some way to the ProTracker's
vertical-blanking speed (e.g. F06).  A value of 6 will skip 5 events
between each displayed event. In other words, each 6th event is displayed.
This will quantize the instrument to 16th notes because 24 events make up a
quarter note.

@{i}TIP:@{ui} Say you just wrote a drum track using a resolution value of 6 and
you now want to have some 32th notes in it. In 16th quantization
(resolution 6,) this is not possible, but if you set the resolution to 3,
you can now enter in 32th notes. Your previously edited notes are still
there, they just appear more spread out because you have zoomed into the
pattern.


SEE ALSO  @{" Resolution example " link "resolution-example"}

@Endnode
@Node "resolution-example" "Resolution example"

@{u}Example for the resolution of a pattern@{uu}


Let's say, resolution is set to 6 (PT-freaks: this is speed F06).


  000  C-5    Between the event 000 and 001 there are 5 more events.
  001  ---    They are not displayed but they are played.
  002  OFF
  003  ---
  ...


If @{" Quantize Record " link "scalednoterec"} is enabled, all your recorded notes will be 
quantized to the resolution value (No notes will be entered in between the
displayed events.) If quantize is disabled, all notes are are recorded at
the highest resolution available and may actually be in between events if
you are at a resolution other than one.

@Endnode
@Node "sdump" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}Sample Dump Window@{uu}

Sample Dump is for synths that understand the Sample Dump Standard (SDS).
SDS is a transmission-protocol to transfer samples via midi. In an open
midi-loop there is no handshaking, but in a closed loop there is.

If your synth doesn't support SDS, this window is useless for you and
dumping a sample to non-SDS-equipment (or requesting a sample) will result
in a timeout message.

You are able to continue editing your song while sending or receiving a
Sample Dump.

@{u}Gadgets@{uu}

  @{" Sample filename " link "sdumpfile"}
  @{" Sample buffer " link "smpbuffer"}
  @{" Raw file " link "sdumpraw"}
  @{" Handshake " link "handshake"}
  @{" Sample number " link "sdumpsample"}
  @{" Sysex ID " link "sdssysexid"}
  @{" Saver " link "sdumpsaver"}

  @{" Rate " link "sdumprate"}
  @{" Length " link "sdumplength"}
  @{" Loop Start " link "sdumplstart"}
  @{" Loop End " link "sdumplend"}

  @{"  Dump  " link "sdumpdump"}
  @{" Request " link "sdumpreq"}
  @{" Abort " link "sdumpabort"}


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F4

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpfile" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Sample filename@{uu}

Select the file you want MidiTracker to dump to your midi equipment.
MidiTracker tests the file automatically before attempting a send.
MidiTracker recognizes the following sample-types:

  · AIFF (16-bit)
  · MAUD (Toccata-style, 16-bit)
  · IFF-8SVX (8/16-bit)
  · WAVE (8/16-bit)
  · VOC (Creative Voice File, 8-bit)
  · Dump files (16-bit RAW, little or big endian)
  · Raw Files (8-bit)

All sample-types are supported mono only. If MidiTracker cannot identify
the file as one of the above, it is treated as a raw file. If you are
sending a raw file you might want to @{" switch " link "sdumpraw"} between 8-bit and 16-bit 
data manually.

@Endnode
@Node "smpbuffer" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Dump sample buffer@{uu}

This gadget is enabled only if @{" Sample-editor " link "sproc"} is open and is holding a sample.
Check this gadget if you wish to dump the sample you have just edited in
the sample processor. Some other gadgets will disable while the Sample
buffer gadget is checked.

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpraw" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Raw mode@{uu}

This gadget is enabled only if your chosen sample (from disk, not from the
sample editor) is a raw-file. In this case, MidiTracker could not identify
it to a known format so it is up to you to decide whether this file is
8-bit or 16-bit.

@Endnode
@Node "handshake" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Handshake@{uu}

For safety transfers, check this if you use a closed midi-loop
(Amiga-midi-out to synth-midi-in, synth-midi-out to Amiga-midi-in.)
Sample-Dump is performed via packets and by checking the handshake-gadget,
acknowledge-packets are received from the other device.

When this gadget is not checked the data direction is one-way and no
acknowledge-packets are sent.

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpsample" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Sample number@{uu}

Enter the preset number of the desired sample you want your synth to
dump, or the preset number to dump the sample into. A value of 0 means
your synth should use next available position.

@Endnode
@Node "sdssysexid" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}SysEx ID@{uu}

Enter here the SysEx ID of your Sampler's sample dump channel. If your
midi equipment supports Sample Dump Standard, it should have an option
somewhere to identify its sample dump channel.

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpsaver" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Sample dump saver@{uu}

This gadget is used to select the save format of the incoming sample dumps.
It is used in conjunction with the @{" Request " link "sdumpreq"} gadget.

@Endnode
@Node "sdumprate" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Sample rate@{uu}

This is the frequency of the sample to dump.

@Endnode
@Node "sdumplength" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Sample length@{uu}

The length of the sample to dump in @{" frames " link "frame"}.

@Endnode
@Node "sdumplstart" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Loop start@{uu}

This is the starting @{" frame " link "frame"} of the loop. If your sample is not a
loop, then this value should be set to the sample-length.


SEE ALSO  @{" Loop end " link "sdumplend"}

@Endnode
@Node "sdumplend" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Loop end@{uu}

This is the last @{" frame " link "frame"} of the loop.


SEE ALSO  @{" Loop start " link "sdumplstart"}

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpdump" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Start dumping@{uu}

Hitting dump will, if a file is selected, dump the sample to midi. If the 
@{" Samplebuffer " link "smpbuffer"} gadget is enabled, MidiTracker will dump the 
@{"sample-editor " link "sproc"}'s contents instead of the file.


SEE ALSO  @{" Sample number " link "sdumpsample"}  @{" Sample editor " link "sproc"}

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpreq" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Request sample@{uu}

Use this to receive sample data from your synth. A file requester will
appear asking you to choose a file to dump to. The Amiga will then ask your
synth to dump the sample given by the @{" sample-number " link "sdumpsample"} gadget. If your 
synth is not able to satisfy this request for some reason, an error-message
will appear.


SEE ALSO  @{" Sample number " link "sdumpsample"}

@Endnode
@Node "sdumpabort" "SAMPLE DUMP WINDOW"

@{u}Abort sample dump@{uu}

This gadget is enabled while dumping only. Hit it to abort the current dump
in progress.

@Endnode
@Node "csources" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}Controlsources graphics display@{uu}

This window is used to graphically input midi controlsource values
manually. The title bar's offset value is for when the pattern size is too
big to fit in the display and the offset value shows the starting event of
the display.

@{u}The graphics area display@{uu}

The current controlsource plot is shown here. The top of the display is
127, and the bottom is 0. So to draw a volume fade-in you would draw from
bottom left to top right.

There are 5 blue vertical lines indicating the location of the five navigation
function keys (see @{" Navigation Hotkeys " link "navigate"}). The current event position is shown
by an additional vertical white line following the editmode-cursor and when
playing a pattern or a song.

If the controlsource is in it's center position (ie. pitchbend wheel at
rest,) the controlsource plots the value in white. A pitchbend in the
center position for an entire pattern would be a white horizontal line.

@{u}Gadgets@{uu}

  @{" List of Controlsources " link "cslistview"}
  @{" Drawmode " link "pgfxdrawmode"}
  @{" Clear " link "pgfxclear"}
  @{" Add Controlsource " link "newcs"}
  @{" Delete Controlsource " link "delcs"}

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F4

@Endnode
@Node "cslistview" "CONTROLSOURCE GRAPHICAL DISPLAY"

@{u}Controlsources list@{uu}

Select the controlsource you wish to edit or view. In the main window's
track display, the controlsource-column will also change depending on what
you select in the controlsource list.

The character in front of each controlsource name indicates its state:

  (blank)       Controlsource is empty.
  * (asterisk)  Controlsource contains data, and is un-muted.
  - (hyphen)    Controlsource contains data, and is muted.


SEE ALSO  @{" New controlsource " link "newcs"} @{" Delete controlsource " link "delcs"}
          @{" Clear controlsource " link "pgfxclear"}

@Endnode
@Node "pgfxdrawmode" "CONTROLSOURCE GRAPHICAL DISPLAY"

@{u}Drawmodes@{uu}

@{u}Dots@{uu}

This is the mode to use if you want to draw 'freehand' curves. Simply use
your mouse in the graphics area whilst using the left mouse button to draw.
Each time you release the left mouse button the display is updated so you can
see how your drawing has been processed.

@{u}Lines@{uu}

Use the left mouse button to select different points in the graphics area
and MidiTracker will connect the two points with a line. Hit the right
mouse button to stop drawing.

@Endnode
@Node "pgfxclear" "CONTROLSOURCE GRAPHICAL DISPLAY"

@{u}Clear controlsource@{uu}

This button clears the current controlsource track, just like @{" Cut track " link "cuttrack"} 
(@{" main window menu " link "mainmenus"}) does. Only the current instrument is processed.

@Endnode
@Node "newcs" "CONTROLSOURCE GRAPHICAL DISPLAY"

@{u}Add controlsource@{uu}

Used to add a new controlsource for the current song. MidiTracker will
display a window with all 127 controlsources for you to select from.

Example controlsource values are:  ModWheel 1, Volume 7, Sustain 64, etc..

SEE ALSO  @{" Delete controlsource " link "delcs"}

@Endnode
@Node "delcs" "CONTROLSOURCE GRAPHICAL DISPLAY"

@{u}Delete controlsource@{uu}

The current controlsource will be removed from the @{" list " link "cslistview"}. Be careful 
when deleting controlsources, because after you confirm the delete the
current controlsource is removed from all instruments, in all patterns, in
the current song!

SEE ALSO  @{" New controlsource " link "newcs"}

@Endnode
@Node "MIDIfilter" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}MIDI Filters@{uu}

This is where you can filter out midi note events, program changes and
control sources for any of the 16 midi channels. You have different filters
for midi input and output, so use the cycle gadget at the top left of the
screen to select between these two pages. You have to set the filters
separately for input and output.

To the left of the check boxes is the list of midi events you may filter.
The bottom left cycle gadget will contain all the current control sources
in your @{" controlsources " link "csources"} window and new control sources are automatically 
added to this gadget when added in the control source window.

If a box is checked, then this midi event will be filtered out for that
channel. The 'All' button inverts the current state of all the filters for
that control source.

You may disable the input/output filters by using the global enable check
boxes at the top of the window. If the box is checked then all filters are
active.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F1

@Endnode
@Node "remapper" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}Channel Stacker/Remapper@{uu}

This is the final process midi data passes through before going to your
synth. Also by using the midi thru and midi filter settings you can build a
virtual midi patchbay to control different pieces of equipment in your
setup from a master controller. The following items appear in the Stacker
Remapper window :

@{u}Instruments@{uu}

This is where you select the current instrument to be remapped. Click on
the instrument number to select. The instrument description will appear
below the selector if you have named the instrument.

@{u}Destination MIDI Channels@{uu}

This is the midi destination(s) of the currently selected instrument.
By default it is set to be the same midi channel as instrument number but
you may select different destination channels and even multiple channels to
create a midi stack for each instrument. Click on the midi channel number
to select the destination channels. Selected channels are highlighted in
white.

@{u}Transpose@{uu}

This enables you to transpose the destination midi channel. This is
independent to any transposing you do in the main window and is
non-destructive. The note events are transposed real time as the song plays
and no events are altered within the song.

The transpose value is given in semi-tones. Arrows are half-note-steps,
double-arrows are octave steps. eg. -12 is transpose one octave down.

@{u}MIDI Thru@{uu}

The midi-thru switch enables the echoing of all entered midi events. This
means all incoming data on this instrument is immediately sent to midi-out
taking into account it's midi remapping and transposition settings.

See @{" Midi Mode " link "MIDImode"} for more information on how midi THRU events are
handled by MidiTracker.

@{u}Global Thru@{uu}

Use Global-thru to enable/disable all midi thru functions. 

@{u}Channel Selecter@{uu}

This is where you select the midi channel number to transpose. Please note
it is the midi destination channel you are transposing and not the
instrument number. This is because you could have multiple instruments
remapped to the same midi channel and you can only transpose it once. ;-)

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F8

@Endnode
@Node "sysexED" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}SysEx Message Editor@{uu}

This window enables you to send, receive and save midi sysex messages. The
listview displays all the current messages in memory and you may highlight
the message you wish to save, dump, delete or rename.

Double-click an entry to rename it.

The list entries have the following syntax: aaaaaa/bbb: <sysex name>
aaaaaa is the length in bytes and bbb the number of messages.

To get sysex from your synth select @{b}New@{ub}, then a requester will ask you to
initiate the dump from your synth. Once the message is received you will
be asked to enter a name for that message. Note that a sysex entry can
consist of more than one Sysex message.

If @{u}auto-detect@{uu} is enabled and you are recording a new sysex, MT will
receive sysex until MIDI data stops for 2 seconds.

The @{u}Time between Sysex messages@{uu} field shows the number of ticks
(1 tick = 1/50 second) between sending two sysex messages. Some keyboards
(K2000, MC303) require a little extra time between receiving consecutive
messages.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F9

@Endnode
@Node "cscope" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}Channelscope Mixdown@{uu}

The window's title contains the selected meter mode and current pattern
number.

@{u}Channelscope levels@{uu}

There are 16 meters representing midi data levels for each midi channel.
If a note is triggered, the current channel's level will raise to indicate
the note event (depending on the velocity of the current note.)

@{u}Channel sliders@{uu}

Use the slider-gadgets to adjust each midi channel's volume in realtime.
These sliders are GLOBAL and operate as the midi channel level for the
entire song. The numbers under the sliders indicate the current midi volume
for that channel. 

Please note that the volume levels are not set seperately for each
instrument. This is because you could have two instruments remapped to the
same midi channel and only ONE volume level is allowed per midi channel.
Therefore the volume controls have to be for each midi channel. 

Just to make things a little more confusing(!) by default the 16
instruments are mapped to the 16 midi channels and each slider would
actually appear to adjust the level for each instrument. :-) Any questions?
Email me sjw@mailbox.uq.edu.au (Scott Watson)

@{u}Other Gadgets@{uu}

  @{" Channel status boxes " link "chocolatebar"}
  @{" All channels play " link "allchansplay"}
  @{" Level style " link "levelstyle"}

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F3

@Endnode
@Node "chocolatebar" "CHANNEL SCOPE MIXDOWN"

@{u}The Chocolate Bar@{uu}

Mute/un-mute each instrument independently by clicking the according piece
of chocolate. :-) It is important to note that the gadgets represent the 16
instruments and NOT the 16 midi channels, like the volume sliders. If you
wish to mute a midi channel use the @{" Midi Filter " link "midifilter"} settings or slide 
it's volume to 0.

Only instruments that contain note events can be toggled. Here's what the
different status boxes mean :

@{i}Empty Gadget@{ui}

	No note data is present in the current instrument.

@{i}White Note Symbol@{ui}
	
	The instrument contains midi data of some kind. Disabled
        instruments will have a ghosted note-image in the gadget.

@{i}White Note Symbol with cross through it@{ui}

	The instrument contains midi data but is currently muted. Using
        the left mouse button on the gadget will mute/unmute each
        instrument.

@{i}Blue@{ui}   
        The blue box indicates the current instrument is displayed in the
        main window. You can use the right mouse button to select other
        instruments in the Channelscope. This is the same as using main
        window's @{" channel slider " link "channel"} or its @{" hotkeys " link "navigate"} on the keypad. 
        Both empty and note event boxes can be blue because all
        instruments are selectable.

The chocolate bar gadgets are LOCAL to the current pattern. This means
that each pattern has its own settings. If you switch to another pattern,
the mute status for all instruments are remembered for that particular
pattern.

Please note that the @{" channel sliders " link "chansliders"} are GLOBAL and affect
the midi volume for the entire song.

@{u}Solo instrument@{uu}

Clicking on a chocolate gadget while holding a SHIFT key will toggle solo
mode for the instrument. It also becomes the current instrument.


SEE ALSO  @{" Solo instrument gadget (main window) " link "solo"}

@Endnode
@Node "allchansplay" "CHANNEL SCOPE MIXDOWN"

@{u}All instruments to playmode@{uu}

This will enable all instruments that are currently muted.


SEE ALSO  @{" Status chocolate bar " link "chocolatebar"}

@Endnode
@Node "levelstyle" "CHANNEL SCOPE MIXDOWN"

@{u}Level style@{uu}

This cyclegadget lets you choose your favorite level style. The current
style is displayed in window's title. Just give it a try!

Feel free to tell me your favorite level styles and I may put them in!  (I
like demo-coding parts ;-) )

@Endnode
@Node "sproc" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}16bit Sample Processor@{uu}

The @{i}Display@{ui} value in the title bar shows the current number of @{" frames " link "frame"}
being displayed.

@{u}Menus of the Sample editor@{uu}

     @{b}Sample@{ub}           @{b}Settings@{ub}            @{b}Edit@{ub}
 @{" Open         " link "opensample"} @{" Cut Into Buffer    " link "smpcuttobuffer"} @{" Octave up   " link "smpoctup"}
 @{" Unload       " link "unloadsample"} @{" Auto zoom          " link "smpautozoom"} @{" Octave down " link "smpoctdown"}
        @{"" link ""}        @{" DUMP endian toggle " link "smpendian"}       @{"" link ""}
 @{" Save DUMP    " link "savedump"} @{" Low-Pass Filter    " link "smplowpass"} @{" Volume 200% " link "smpvol200"}
 @{" Save AIFF    " link "saveaiff"}           @{"" link ""}           @{" Volume  50% " link "smpvol50"}
 @{" Save MAUD    " link "savemaud"} @{" Sample rate        " link "smpratemenu"} @{" Volume any% " link "smpvolany"} 
        @{"" link ""}                  @{"" link ""}
 @{" Close window " link "close16bitwindow"} @{" Boost              " link "smpboost"}
        @{"" link ""}        @{" Filter             " link "smpfilter"}
        @{"" link ""}        @{" Flip               " link "smpflip"}                  

The main area of the window contains the sample data (if loaded.) You can
mark a range with your mouse by clicking into the display and highlighting
part of the sample.

@{u}Gadgets@{uu}

  @{" Zoom in     " link "zoomin"} @{" Play Display " link "playdisplay"} @{" Loop type   " link "looptype"} @{" Cut     " link "smpcut"} @{" Copy    " link "smpcopy"}
  @{" Zoom out    " link "zoomout"} @{" Play Range   " link "playrange"} @{" Stop        " link "stopsample"} @{" Paste   " link "smppaste"} @{" Mix     " link "smpmix"}
  @{" Show all    " link "showall"} @{" Play all     " link "playall"} @{" Range all   " link "rangeall"} @{" Cut out " link "smpcutout"}
  
  @{" Sample name                             " link "currentsample"}  @{" Rate " link "smprate"}

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F5

@Endnode
@Node "frame" "What's a frame?"

@{u}Frame@{uu}

A frame of a 16bit-sample is 2 bytes = 1 word.

A frame of an 8bit-sample is 1 byte.

@Endnode
@Node "zoomin" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Zoom in gadget@{uu}

This function will expand your marked range to cover the full display, like
zooming into the range.

SEE ALSO  @{" Zoom out " link "zoomout"}

@Endnode
@Node "zoomout" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Zoom out gadget@{uu}

This is the opposite of Zoom-In. The display will show the active range
before you zoomed in.


SEE ALSO  @{" Zoom in " link "zoomin"}

@Endnode
@Node "showall" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Show all gadget@{uu}

The entire sample is displayed as is.

@Endnode
@Node "currentsample" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Load new sample@{uu}

Type in the sample name you wish to load. You can also use the button
gadget to bring up a file requester.

@{" Open sample " link "opensample"} in the menus is same function.

@Endnode
@Node "playdisplay" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Play display gadget@{uu}

Play the current display. Nothing outside the display is played.

The @{" Loop type " link "looptype"} setting has no effect on play display.

@Endnode
@Node "playrange" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Play range gadget@{uu}

Play the currently marked range.

The @{" Loop type " link "looptype"} setting has no effect on play range.

@Endnode
@Node "playall" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Play all gadget@{uu}

Play the entire sample.

The @{" Loop type " link "looptype"} indicates how the sample should loop.

@Endnode
@Node "looptype" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Loop type gadget@{uu}

Choose how you want the sample to be looped. Currently supported values
are:

  Off      - will produce a single playback pass.
  Forward - if the sample-end is reached the framepointer restarts at the
             loop-start point, plays till the loop-end point, and then
             continually loops from the loop-start to the loop-end points.

@Endnode
@Node "stopsample" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Stop sample gadget@{uu}

The sample playback is stopped.

@Endnode
@Node "rangeall" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Range all gadget@{uu}

The entire display is marked as a range. 

@Endnode
@Node "smpcut" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Cut range@{uu}

Cut marked range. It is not cleared, but cut into the @{" sample cut buffer " link "smpcuttobuffer"}.


SEE ALSO  @{" Paste range " link "smppaste"} @{" Copy range " link "smpcopy"}
          @{" Cut into buffer " link "smpcuttobuffer"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpcopy" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Copy range@{uu}

Copy the marked range into the internal buffer. This is used in conjunction
with @{" paste " link "smppaste"} function to rearrange a sample.


SEE ALSO  @{" Cut range " link "smpcut"} @{" Paste range " link "smppaste"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpcutout" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Cut out range@{uu}

Everything but the marked range is deleted and the marked range becomes the
full sample. Please note that this cut does NOT copy any data to the sample
copy buffer.

@Endnode
@Node "smprate" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Sample rate gadget@{uu}

Enter your desired playback-frequency, in samples-per-second. i.e. Hertz.
There are preset sample rates in the @{" sample rate menu " link "smpratemenu"} if
you wish to choose them.

@Endnode
@Node "smpmix" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Mix range@{uu}

Mix the internal buffer with the marked range.

@Endnode
@Node "smppaste" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR"

@{u}Paste buffer@{uu}

Insert the internal buffer at marked range-start. This means it is inserted
in front of your currently marked range.


SEE ALSO  @{" Cut range " link "smpcut"} @{" Copy range " link "smpcopy"}

@Endnode
@Node "opensample" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Open sample@{uu}

Load a new sample (must be 16bit only!) Supported formats are
AIFF/MAUD/DUMP. (DUMP is just a raw file(no header))


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + o

@Endnode
@Node "unloadsample" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Unload sample@{uu}

Clear the entire sample buffer and free all associated memory.

@Endnode
@Node "savedump" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Save DUMP sample@{uu}

Save sample as a 16bit raw file. The @{" endian " link "smpendian"} setting decides
how sample-words are saved (little/big endian).


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + 1

@Endnode
@Node "saveaiff" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Save AIFF sample@{uu}

Save sample as AIFF file.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + 2

@Endnode
@Node "savemaud" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Save MAUD sample@{uu}

Save sample as MAUD file. This file type is supported by the Toccata audio
board.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + 3

@Endnode
@Node "close16bitwindow" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

Close the sample processor window

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + q

@Endnode
@Node "smpcuttobuffer" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Cut to buffer@{uu}

If enabled, @{" Cut range " link "smpcut"} will cut the marked range to the internal
buffer.

@Endnode
@Node "smpratemenu" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Sample rate@{uu}

Here's a list of commonly used sample frequencies. You can quickly select
them by pressing their menu-hotkeys.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + 7 ( 11025 hz )
@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + 8 ( 22050 hz )
@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + 9 ( 44100 hz )

@Endnode
@Node "smpendian" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Sample endian@{uu}

This menu item is enabled only if a DUMP (raw) sample has been loaded.
Because DUMP samples do not have a header, it is not possible to recognize
their endian type (little or big endian). You can see the different
effects by the sample display:  With the wrong endian, the waveform looks
unnatural. Use this menu item to toggle the endian and the waveform should
look some more "acoustic."

@Endnode
@Node "smplowpass" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Amiga lowpass filter@{uu}

Switch the Amiga's builtin-lowpass filter on/off while playing the sample.
Select "ignore" to leave the filter's state as it is.

@Endnode
@Node "smpautozoom" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - SAMPLE MENU"

@{u}Automatic zooming@{uu}

Each time you mark a range, MidiTracker automatically zooms into this range.
This is good if you want to approach a very small range from within a large
sample.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + z

SEE ALSO  @{" Zoom in " link "zoomin"} @{" Zoom out " link "zoomout"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpoctup" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Octave Up@{uu}

Pitch the entire sample one octave up (ie cut every second @{" frame " link "frame"}.)

@Endnode
@Node "smpoctdown" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Octave Down@{uu}

Pitch the entire sample one octave down (ie double every @{" frame " link "frame"}.)

@Endnode
@Node "smpvol200" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Double volume@{uu}

Double sample's amplitude. If the amplitude exceeds the dynamic range,
then the waveform will be clipped.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + '+'

SEE ALSO  @{" Halve volume " link "smpvol50"} @{" Any volume " link "smpvolany"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpvol50" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Halve volume@{uu}

Halve waveform's amplitude.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + '-'

SEE ALSO  @{" Double volume " link "smpvol200"} @{" Any volume " link "smpvolany"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpvolany" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Any volume@{uu}

Recalculate the sample's amplitude as a percentage of its current
amplitude. You will be requested to enter a percent value.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + v

SEE ALSO  @{" Double volume " link "smpvol200"} @{" Halve volume " link "smpvol50"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpboost" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Boost sample@{uu}

Boosts the entire sample. After this it should sound a little bit louder
and clearer.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + b

SEE ALSO  @{" Filter " link "smpfilter"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpfilter" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

@{u}Lowpass filter@{uu}

Perform lowpass-filter on the sample. This is not the Amiga's internal
power-LED-filter, but actually a mathematical filter that changes you
sample.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + l

SEE ALSO  @{" Boost " link "smpboost"}

@Endnode
@Node "smpflip" "16 BIT SAMPLE PROCESSOR - EDIT MENU"

Flip sample

Flip the whole sample, so it is playing in reverse (nice for drumloops :)


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + f

@Endnode
@Node "k2k" "Kurzweil K2000 dialog window"

@{u}Kurzweil K2000 window@{uu}

@{u}SysEx ID@{uu}

Select the SysEx-ID of your K2000. The value of this gadget must match
the SysEx-ID of the K2000 you are currently transferring data to (watch the
Midi/Receive-page there).

@{u}Refresh listview@{uu}

Refresh the K2000 programs display. MidiTracker will send some requests
to the K2000 (the one with your SysEx-ID ) to retrieve information about
the programs residing there. This function will take a few seconds
depending on how many programs are currently in your K2000.

@{u}Program selection@{uu}

For this gadget to be active you hit the refresh gadget first. Then by
clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your K2000. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled, 
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "boehm" "Boehm dialog window"

@{u}Boehm 12/24 window@{uu}

@{u}Program selection@{uu}

By clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your Boehm. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled, 
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "mc303" "Roland MC-303 Groovebox"

@{u}Roland MC-303 window@{uu}

@{u}Program selection@{uu}

By clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your MC-303. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled, 
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "yamahaxg" "Yamaha XG"

@{u}Yamaha XG window@{uu}

@{u}Program selection@{uu}

By clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your Yamaha. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled, 
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "quasar" "Quasimidi Quasar"

@{u}Quasimidi Quasar window@{uu}

@{u}Program selection@{uu}

By clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your Quasar. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled, 
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "cs1x" "Yahama CS1x"

@{u}Yamaha CS1x window@{uu}

@{u}Program selection@{uu}

By clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your CS1x. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled, 
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "quadra" "Alesis Quadrasynth dialog window"

@{u}Alesis Quadrasynth window@{uu}

@{u}Refresh listview@{uu}

Refresh all entries in the big listview-gadget. MidiTracker will attempt
to read ALL Singles residing in your Quadrasynth. This procedure will take
about 16 seconds.

@{u}Single selection@{uu}

For this gadget to be active you hit the refresh gadget first. Then by 
clicking one of the listview's entries, MidiTracker will send the
corresponding program changes to your Quadrasynth. If @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} is enabled,
this program number is also put into the preset-track.


 Back to @{" Synth support " link "synths"}

@Endnode
@Node "editprefs" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}Edit Preferences@{uu}

All changes will become active immediately!  This means you can leave this
window open and try out the new values.

  @{" Cut to buffers               " link "cuttobuffers"}
  @{" Join has Overlay Priority    " link "joindoesoverlay"}
  @{" Cut instrument before record " link "cutbeforerec"}
  @{" Auto velocity                " link "autovel"}
  @{" Pattern size Delta           " link "pattsizeD"}
  @{" First Auto Velocity          " link "firstavel"}
  @{" Maximum Tracks               " link "maxtracks"}
  @{" Highlight Resolution         " link "hiliteres"}
  @{" Default Resolution           " link "defaultres"}
  @{" Default Patternsize          " link "defaultpattsize"}
  @{" Tabulator skip               " link "tab2note"}

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + e

@Endnode
@Node "MIDIprefs" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}MIDI Preferences@{uu}

  @{" Panic method              " link "panicmethod"} @{" Panic controllers         " link "panicmode"}
  @{" MIDI Mode                 " link "MIDImode"} @{" Send sequencer start/stop " link "sendseq"}
  @{" Playback clock            " link "playclock"} @{" Auto Rewind               " link "autorewind"}
  @{" Record clock              " link "recclock"} @{" Stop at pattern's end     " link "stoppatternsend"} 
  @{" Program changes           " link "progchangetype"} @{" Send MIDI Time Code       " link "mtc"}
