                @{"" link ""}                           @{"" link ""}
                @{"" link ""}              @{" Record buffer size        " link "recbufsize"}
                @{"" link ""}              @{" Audition Passes           " link "audpasses"}


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + m

@Endnode
@Node "sysprefs" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU"

@{u}System Preferences@{uu}

  @{"          ARexx port         " link "arexxgad"}
  @{" Screenfont  " link "screenfont"} @{" Patternfont  " link "pattfont"}
  @{" Compressor  " link "compressor"} @{" XPK save     " link "xpksave"}
         @{"" link ""}       @{" Create icons " link "saveicons"}
         @{"" link ""}       @{" PC Keyboard  " link "pckeyboard"}
         @{"" link ""}

          @{" GM bars per pattern " link "gmbarsperpattern"}
          @{" Hide method         " link "hidemethod"}
          @{" Midi access         " link "midiaccess"}
          @{" Use Samples         " link "usesamples"}

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + p

@Endnode
@Node "cuttobuffers" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Cut to buffers@{uu}

When enabled, all cut operations will first copy the current track,
instrument, or pattern before erasing it from the pattern.

@{" Block operations " link "mainmenus"} are affected by this setting too.

@Endnode
@Node "joindoesoverlay" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Join does Overlay@{uu}

This switch decides what action to take if data from the copy-buffer
collides with data in current work tracks. When enabled, the buffer's data
overwrites worktrack's data.

@Endnode
@Node "cutbeforerec" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Cut instrument before recording@{uu}

The current instrument data is cut before the next record pass. This is
only for pattern record mode.

@Endnode
@Node "autovel" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Automatic velocity@{uu}

When enabled newly entered notes automatically get the velocity value of
the previous note in the same track. This is in editmode only and for
notes entered from the Amiga keyboard.

If you enter the first note in the current track, the value of 
@{" First Auto velocity " link "firstavel"} will be used.

@Endnode
@Node "firstavel" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}First auto-velocity@{uu}

This is the default velocity used for notes entered from the Amiga
keyboard. See @{" Auto velocity " link "autovel"} for more information.

@Endnode
@Node "pattsizeD" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Pattern size delta-value@{uu}

This value is added or subtracted from the main window's @{" pattern size " link "pattsize"}
gadget when you use the arrow buttons beside it.

@Endnode
@Node "hiliteres" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Highlight Resolution@{uu}

This will set the highlight resolution value which is used to highlight
particular events in the POS column of the track display.

@{b}TIP:@{ub} Say you zoom into a pattern that is normally at a resolution of 6
and you use a resolution of 3. Every second event will be highlighted to
indicate the corresponding notes for the 6 resolution.

At a resolution of 6 and highlight resolution also set to 6 
(* = highlighted):

  POS
* 000
* 001
* 002
* 003 

Now if we change the resolution to 3 with the highlight resolution still at
6 :

  POS            POS 
* 000 --------> *000
* 001 ------.    001
* 002 ---.  `-> *002
* 003 .  :       003
      :  `----> *004
      :          005
      `-------> *006
                 007
                
This enables you to quickly reference the note timings if you have
different resolution values for different instruments within a pattern.
     
@Endnode
@Node "defaultres" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Default Resolution@{uu}

If a new (empty) instrument is selected, this is its default resolution
value.

@Endnode
@Node "defaultpattsize" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Default Patternsize@{uu}

If a new pattern is selected, this is its default size.


SEE ALSO @{" Default Resolution " link "defaultres"}

@Endnode
@Node "tab2note" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDITING PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Tabulator skipping@{uu}

This setting applies to editmode only. It decides what happens if the TAB
key is pressed (or Shift-TAB, see @{" Navigation hotkeys " link "navigate"}.) The following 
modes are available:

@{i}Tab to note@{ui}         The cursor jumps to the note column.

@{i}Tab to Velocity@{ui}     The cursor jumps to the velocity column.

@Endnode
@Node "recbufsize" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Record buffersize@{uu}

Set the record buffersize in kilobytes (kB).


SEE ALSO @{" How to record " link "recording"}

@Endnode
@Node "screenfont" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Screen font@{uu}

Used to select the font that is used by the screen, its windows and
gadgets. Currently the font's height is limited to 8. It can be
fixed-width or proportional.


SEE ALSO  @{" Pattern font " link "pattfont"}

@Endnode
@Node "pattfont" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Pattern font@{uu}

This font is for the track display in @{" main window " link "mainwindow"}. It must be a 
fixed-size font at a height of 8.


SEE ALSO  @{" Screen font " link "screenfont"}

@Endnode
@Node "arexxgad" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}ARexx port name@{uu}

Enter the new name of MidiTracker's @{" ARexx " link "arexx"} port.

@Endnode
@Node "panicmethod" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Panic method@{uu}

In case of the dreaded note-hang, MidiTracker will allow you to transmit
two different @{" panic " link "panic"} methods:

@{u}Standard@{uu}

Send a standard panic-message to all channels. Your synth must understand
these commands for the panic to be effective, so try it out to see whether
or not your synth understands it. This option is much quicker than the
overkill solution.

(For tech-heads:  All-notes-off is :  $Bx $7B $00 where x is $0-$F. With
an @{" all-controllers-off " link "panicmode"} it is:  $Bx $7B $00 $79 $00 where x is $0-$F.)

@{u}Overkill@{uu}

Send LOTS of Note-OFF messages to each midi channel. For each note 
(C-0 to B-9) on all 16 midi channels, a Note-OFF is sent. If 
@{" all-controllers-off " link "panicmode"} is enabled, all controlsources are reset manually.

@Endnode
@Node "panicmode" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Panic Controllers@{uu}

If you press @{" panic " link "panic"}, an All-notes-off command is sent to midi.
Enable this switch if you also an all-controllers-off message to be sent.
This will reset all supported controllers.


SEE ALSO  @{" Panic method " link "panicmethod"}

@Endnode
@Node "MIDImode" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Midi Mode@{uu}

This is how MidiTracker uses incoming note data for note entry during
editing/recording and for THRU routing. There are two modes available :-

1) MULTI MODE - MIDI INPUT CHANNEL x -----> MIDITRACKER INSTRUMENT x ONLY!

	- If you transmit on midi channel one from your synth, MidiTracker
          will only enter the data if you are currently in instrument one.
          This applies to both edit and record modes.
	
	- The THRU routing depends on the midi transmit channel on your
	  synth. So if you play on midi channel two and instrument two 
          has THRU active, then the 'Midi Out Destination Channel' for 
          instrument two is played.

	EXAMPLE : If you have a tone module that is receiving on channel
          eight and you want to control it via a master keyboard, you go to
          instrument eight and turn on THRU in the @{" Stacker/Remapper " link "remapper"}
          window.  Now select transmit midi channel eight on your
          controller and you should be able to play the tone module.

2) OMNI MODE -  MIDI INPUT 'ANY' CHANNEL --> CURRENT INSTRUMENT

        - MidiTracker will enter data in the currently selected instrument
          even if it's number is different to the transmit midi channel on
          your synth.

        - Midi THRU is identical to MULTI MODE.

3) CHANNEL MODE -  MIDI INPUT 'ANY' CHANNEL --> CURRENT INSTRUMENT 

        - Data entry into the current instrument always happens, regardless
          of the incoming midi channel.

        - If midi-thru is enabled for the *CURRENT* instrument, the event
          is sent to the corresponding "Midi Out Destination Channels", as
          defined on the Stacker/Remapper window for that instrument.

	EXAMPLE: If you always transmit on midi channel one from your
     	  master controller and you wish to play a tone module on channel
 	  four, you select the instrument in MidiTracker that's mapped to
	  midi channel four and the notes from your master controller will
  	  be thru'ed to that channel. So you use the 16 MidiTracker
 	  instruments to select the current instrument to be heard whilst
	  using your master controller.

@Endnode
@Node "xpksave" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}XPK save switch@{uu}

When enabled MidiTracker will xpk-compresses your songs before saving them
to disk. This applies to MidiTracker-songfiles only and not to
General-MIDI files.

If this gadget is checked, the @{" compressor " link "compressor"} gadget next to it is enabled.

@Endnode
@Node "compressor" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Compressor listview@{uu}

Choose your favorite compressor, to compress your songfiles with. This
gadget is only enabled if @{" XPK " link "xpksave"} is enabled.

@Endnode
@Node "hidemethod" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Hiding method@{uu}

The three methods of hiding MidiTracker are :


@{i}Window@{ui}      Opens a little window on the default public screen.
              Hit the zip-gadget (zoom gadget) to uniconify.

@{i}AppMenu@{ui}     MidiTracker adds itself to the Workbench's Tools-menu.
              Select it to uniconify.

@{i}AppIcon@{ui}     Places an application icon on workbench.
              Double-click to uniconify. (not yet implemented)


@Endnode
@Node "gmbarsperpattern" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}GM bars per pattern@{uu}

This is the number of bars MT will put into each pattern when you import a
standard midifile.

@Endnode
@Node "midiaccess" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}MIDI access@{uu}

Choose here the method of accessing the serial hardware:

  - Hardware (will hit the internal serial port directly)
    This method may be slightly faster than Midi-Lib.

  - Midi-Lib (midi.library is required)
    This is the 'system friendly' method.
    If you want to use @{" samples " link "usesamples"} you have to choose midi.library.

@Endnode
@Node "usesamples" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Use samples with Midi-Lib@{uu}

Using an amiga sample player program you can trigger amiga samples from
within Miditracker. Try out the following programs :-

"Sample-X" by Sheun Olatunbosun.

or

"MidiIn" by Rafal Michalski.


If this checkbox is enabled, MidiTracker will set up an external MidiOut
port called "MidiTracker". Within the sample player you select this port to
enable Miditracker to talk to it. You also have to enable the @{" Midi-Lib " link "midiaccess"} 
setting to be able to use amiga samples. Please read the sample-player's
documentation for more information.

@Endnode
@Node "pckeyboard" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}PC Keyboard@{uu}

If this option is enabled, the numeric keypad is mapped differently to
support PC keyboards. See the @{" hotkeys " link "hotkeys"} table for the PC key mapping.

@Endnode
@Node "maxtracks" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - EDIT PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Maximum number of tracks@{uu}

This is the maximum number of tracks per instrument. The range is 6 to
infinity but keep in mind the less tracks you use the faster MidiTracker
can process each pattern. You may supply a default value at the @{" startup " link "start"}.

@Endnode
@Node "saveicons" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - SYSTEM PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Save icons@{uu}

Select this gadget to @{" save your songs " link "savesong"} with a project-icon.
(Not yet implemented.)

@Endnode
@Node "mtc" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Send MIDI Time Code@{uu}

If activated, MidiTracker will transmit a MTC for external midi equipment
to "lock" onto the song playback. MTC messages are sent 25 times a second.

@Endnode
@Node "ignorenoteoffs" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Ignore note-OFFs@{uu}

Incoming Note-OFF messages are ignored. This happens in both record and
edit modes.

@Endnode
@Node "playdisabled" "Play disabled tracks"

@{u}Play disabled tracks@{uu}

All tracks and instruments are played back, even if they are supposed to be
muted.

@{b}TIP:@{ub} Let's say you've muted some tracks or instruments because you are
performing and want to play a particular instrument's part live. Now a few
days later you want to create a demo tape or a demo cd and you need to
enable the instrument(s) you disabled for the live performance, but there
are many patterns you have to find and enable instruments on. With this
switch enabled, ALL channels and their tracks are played despite their mute
status. Everything is played back. Nice huh?

@Endnode
@Node "playclock" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Playback clock@{uu}

@{u}External@{uu}

MidiTracker will listen and synchronize to external midi clock messages. You
should configure your synth to send these clocks, otherwise MidiTracker
will not play.

@{u}Internal@{uu}

MidiTracker will generate and send clock messages. In this state it is
ignoring external clocks.

@Endnode
@Node "recclock" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Record clock@{uu}

@{u}External@{uu}

MidiTracker will listen and synchronize to external midi clock messages.
This is useful for recording songs or sequences from your synth's
builtin-sequencer. You should configure your synth to send these clocks,
otherwise MidiTracker will not record.

@{u}Internal@{uu}

MidiTracker will generate and record internal midi clock messages. In this
state it is ignoring external clocks.

@Endnode
@Node "sendseq" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Send sequencer start/stop@{uu}

If enabled, realtime sysex-commands are sent to midi:

@{i}Start@{ui} ($FA) When you hit play, MidiTracker will send a midi start and
              all connected sequencers will start playing.

@{i}Stop@{ui}  ($FC) When the music is stopped connected sequencers will stop
              playing.


SEE ALSO  @{" Play song " link "playsong"} @{" Play pattern " link "playpatt"} @{" Stop " link "stopbutton"}

@Endnode
@Node "stoppatternsend" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Stop at pattern's end@{uu}

This item decides whether to stop or repeat pattern replay. It is for
@{" Play pattern " link "playpatt"} and @{" Record pattern " link "recpatt"} only. When enabled, replay will 
stop at the end of the pattern, otherwise it will loop until you stop it.

@Endnode
@Node "audpasses" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - MIDI PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Audition Passes@{uu}

This is the number of playback passes in audition record mode. For more
information check out @{" audition record mode" link "recmode"}.

@Endnode
@Node "metro" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - METRONOME PREFERENCES WINDOW"

@{u}Metronome settings@{uu}

@{u}General@{uu}

  @{" Steps           " link "metrostep"} @{" Type            " link "metrotype"} @{" Click for test  " link "clickfortest"}  @{" Count in only   " link "countinonly"}
  @{" Bars            " link "metrobars"} @{" Beats           " link "metrobeats"} @{" Off-beats %     " link "offbeatsvol"}

     @{u}Amiga sample@{uu}      @{u}MIDI click@{uu}

  @{" Sample filename " link "metrosample"}  @{" Bank     " link "metrobank"}
  @{" Audio           " link "metroaudio"}  @{" Preset   " link "metropreset"}
  @{" Volume          " link "metrosmpvol"}  @{" Record   " link "metrorec"}
  @{" Period          " link "metroperiod"}  @{" Note     " link "metronote"}
                      @{" Channel  " link "metrochannel"}
                      @{" Velocity " link "metrovelocity"}


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + p

@Endnode
@Node "metrotype" "Metronome type"

@{u}Metronome type@{uu}

@{u}Sample@{uu}

The sample page (left side) is enabled if "Sample" is chosen from the
cycle gadget. It is still on the @{" to-do-list " link "todo"} :)

@{u}MIDI@{uu}

The midi page (right side) is enabled if "MIDI" is selected in the cycle
gadget. MidiTracker will send Note-ON-messages to the selected note and
midi channel as the metronome click.

@Endnode
@Node "metrobank" "Metronome MIDI bank controller"

@{u}MIDI bank@{uu}

This is the bank number on your synth to select the required preset for
the metronome channel.

@Endnode
@Node "metropreset" "Metronome MIDI preset"

@{u}MIDI Preset@{uu}

This is the program number on your synth to select the required preset for
the metronome channel.

@Endnode
@Node "metrorec" "Metronome Preset Record"

@{u}Metronome Record@{uu}

Here you can record a complete program change from your synth. The
@{" programchange " link "progchangetype"} setting for the channel you are playing
is used. You may play a note too, which is then used with its velocity.

@Endnode
@Node "metronote" "MIDI note"

@{u}MIDI Note@{uu}

This is the midi-note being played as the metronome click. Expected values
must look like: C-5 or F#4, just like in the main window's track display. 

@Endnode
@Node "metrochannel" "Metronome MIDI channel"

@{u}MIDI Channel@{uu}

This is the midi channel you want the metronome played on. You may choose
any of the 16 channels.

@Endnode
@Node "metrovelocity" "Metronome MIDI velocity"

@{u}MIDI Velocity@{uu}

This is the attack velocity for each note. Range is 0 to 127.

@Endnode
@Node "metroaudio" "Sample audio type"

@{u}Sample audio@{uu}

Select left, right, or stereo positioning of the sound sample.

@Endnode
@Node "metrosmpvol" "Metronome sample volume"

@{u}Sample volume@{uu}

Select the volume of the Amiga sample to be played. Range is 0 to 64.

@Endnode
@Node "metroperiod" "Metronome sample period"

@{u}Sample period@{uu}

This is the period of the sample, i.e. playback-speed. This is automatically
set when a sample is loaded. The playback rate is taken from its
IFF-8SVX-header.

@Endnode
@Node "metrosample" "Metronome sample file"

@{u}Sample file@{uu}

Select a sample to use as your metronome. It must be in IFF-8SVX format.

@Endnode
@Node "metrostep" "Metronome steps"

@{u}Steps@{uu}

This is the number of midi clocks between each click. At normal tempo,
a value of 24 represents quarter notes, 12 = 8th notes, 48 = half notes,
and so on.

@Endnode
@Node "clickfortest" "Click it for test"

@{u}Click for test@{uu}

Click here to listen to the metronome but not play the song.

@Endnode
@Node "metrobeats" "Beats per bar"

@{u}Beats@{uu}

Beats is the number of clicks per bar. A value of 4 would sound like
4/4 rhythm and a value of 3 would be some waltz rhythm. The first beat in
a bar is accented with a louder volume. Check out the Off-Beats-vol% for
more information.


SEE ALSO  @{" Bars " link "metrobars"}

@Endnode
@Node "metrobars" "Metronome bars"

@{u}Bars@{uu}

This is the number of bars the metronome is played before the music starts.


SEE ALSO  @{" Beats per bar " link "metrobeats"}

@Endnode
@Node "offbeatsvol" "Off-Beats %"

@{u}Off-Beats Volume@{uu}

This is the percentage of the main velocity for all the non-accented
metronome clicks. Set at 50% with a main velocity of 100 would play like so:

  BEAT 1         BEAT 2	         BEAT 3          BEAT 4

C-5 V=100       C-5 V=50        C-5 V=50        C-5 V=50

V being velocity.

@Endnode
@Node "countinonly" "Count in Metronome"

@{u}Count in only@{uu}

If this checkbox is enabled, MT will play the metronome at count-in only.
The metronome will silence during record.

@Endnode
@Node "keyboardactions" "MAIN SCREEN - SETTINGS MENU - KEYBOARD ACTIONS WINDOW"

@{u}Keyboard Actions@{uu}

This feature allows you to trigger MidiTracker's transport controls via
your midi keyboard. The seven actions available are :-

  · Record Song
  · Record Pattern
  · Play Song
  · Play Pattern
  · Fast Forward
  · Fast Rewind
  · Stop

To assign the midi note for each action you press the record button next to
the action and play the desired note on your midi keyboard. The window has
a global switch to enable/disable all midi transport functions in case you
wish to play those particular notes into MidiTracker. Also, each action has
its own switch to turn it on or off.


@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} ALT + k - Global enable off/on

@Endnode
@Node "score" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}Score Display@{uu}

This is a grid display of the current song with the highlighted boxes
representing patterns that contain note events for that instrument. The
highlighted vertical wire-frame is the current position within the song.
This window is handy if you wish to see at a glance the overall structure
of your song and follow the start and stop times of each instrument as the
song plays.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F6

@Endnode
@Node "activity" "MAIN SCREEN - WINDOWS MENU"

@{u}MIDI activity@{uu}

This window displays the incoming and outgoing midi activity. This is
useful when hunting down midi routing problems and also checking how much
midi data your synth has to sustain. :-) If you are getting an overload of
midi data you may wish to use the @{" midi filters " link "midifilter"} to ease the strain on 
your midi port.

Use the Zoom gadget to scale the display. Clicking into the display will
toggle the two display styles.

@{b}HOTKEY:@{ub} R-AMIGA + F7

@Endnode
@Node "keyboard" "How to utilize your Amiga's keyboard"

@{u}Amiga keyboard functions@{uu}

The @{" navigation " link "navigate"} Keys. 

The @{" hotkeys " link "hotkeys"}.

You are also able to play notes on your Amiga keyboard. In non-editmode,
typed notes are played i.e. Note-ONs are created when the key is pressed
and a Note-OFF is generated when you release the key. Please note that in
editmode you can enter and play notes continually by holding down a key
(which crashes an ensoniq ASR10 quite nicely :-) .

Each key is treated independently, making it possible to play chords!
(Unless you have a crappy A1200 keyboard. :-( ) In editmode Note-ONs and
Note-OFFs are put into the current track. You may also put Note-OFFs into
the track via the "`" key at the top left of your keyboard.

@{u}English Keyboard@{uu}

             c# d# f# g#a# c#'d#'f#'g#'
              | |   | | |   | |   | |

              2 3   5 6 7   9 0   = \      \ upper octave
             Q W E R T Y U I O P [ ]       /

             | | | | | | | | | | | |
             c d e f g a b c'd'e'f'g'



               C# D# F# G#A# c# d#
                | |   | | |   | |

                S D   G H J   L ;          \ lower octave
               Z X C V B N M , . /         /

               | | | | | | | | | |
               C D E F G A B c d e


@{u}German Keyboard@{uu}

             c# d# f# g#a# c#'d#'f#'g#'
              | |   | | |   | |   | |

              2 3   5 6 7   9 0   ´ \      \ upper octave
             Q W E R T Z U I O P Ü +       /

             | | | | | | | | | | | |
             c d e f g a b c'd'e'f'g'



               C# D# F# G#A# c# d#
                | |   | | |   | |

                S D   G H J   L Ö          \ lower octave
               Y X C V B N M , . -         /

               | | | | | | | | | |
               C D E F G A B c d e


@Endnode
@Node "navigate" "Navigation keys"

@{u}MidiTracker Navigation@{uu}

(PT) means keys this is close to ProTracker.

F6  ......................  (PT) Jump to pattern position 0 (1st quarter)
F7  ......................  (PT) Jump to 2nd quarter
F8  ......................  (PT) Jump to 3rd quarter
F9  ......................  (PT) Jump to 4th quarter
F10 ......................  (PT) Jump to end of 4th quarter

SHIFT-F6-F10 .............. (PT) Store current event position into that 
                            function key

ALT-CURSOR-UP ............. Previous song position
Alt-CURSOR-DOWN ........... Next song position
ALT-SHIFT-CURSOR-UP ....... Skip 4 song positions back
ALT-SHIFT-CURSOR-DOWN ..... Skip 4 song positions forward
ALT-SHIFT-CTRL-CURSOR-UP .. Skip to first song position
ALT-SHIFT-CTRL-CURSOR-DOWN  Skip to last song position

ALT-CURSOR-RIGHT .......... (PT) Next pattern
ALT-CURSOR-LEFT ........... (PT) Previous pattern

CTRL-CURSOR-RIGHT ......... Increase pattern Resolution
CTRL-CURSOR-LEFT .......... Decrease pattern Resolution

TAB ....................... (PT) Edit-mode: next track
SHIFT-TAB ................. (PT) Edit-mode: previous Track

CTRL-CURSOR-UP ............ Increment cycle through controlsources
CTRL-CURSOR-DOWN .......... Decrement cycle through controlsources

SHIFT-CURSOR-UP ........... (PT) Scroll 8 events up
SHIFT-CURSOR-DOWN ......... (PT) Scroll 8 events down.


CURSOR LEFT, RIGHT, UP, DOWN :-

(Edit-mode) ............... (PT) Move cursor
(Non-edit-mode) ........... Browse tracks (same use as using the scroller
                                               gadget above trackdisplay)
(Score-Display window) .... Browse positions and instruments.
 

SHIFT-CURSOR LEFT/RIGHT ... Scroll 6 Tracks to the left or right 
                            (non-edit-mode)



SEE ALSO  @{" More hotkeys " link "hotkeys"}

@Endnode
@Node "hotkeys" "Hotkeys"

@{u}Hotkeys@{uu}

(PT) means key(s) similar to ProTracker.

SPACE ..................... (PT) When PLAY/REC: Stop
                            (PT) When STOP: Toggle Editmode

ALT-SPACE ................. Toggle chordmode

AMIGA-SPACE ............... Toggle solo-mode for the current instrument

ESCAPE .................... Panic (all notes off / all controllers off)


F1 ........................ Fast Rewind
F2 ........................ Forward (Fast play)
F3 ........................ Fast Forward (skip to next pattern)
F4 ........................ Play pattern
F5 ........................ Play song
CTRL-F4 ................... Record pattern
CTRL-F5 ................... Record song


SHIFT-F2 .................. Join Track
SHIFT-F3 .................. (PT) Cut Track
SHIFT-F4 .................. (PT) Copy Track
SHIFT-F5 .................. (PT) Paste Track

ALT-F2 .................... Join Instrument
ALT-F3 .................... (PT) Cut Instrument
ALT-F4 .................... (PT) Copy Instrument
ALT-F5 .................... (PT) Paste Instrument

SHIFT-ALT-F2 .............. Join Pattern
SHIFT-ALT-F3 .............. Cut Pattern
SHIFT-ALT-F4 .............. Copy Pattern
SHIFT-ALT-F5 .............. Paste Pattern


CTRL-1 to 9        (PT) Choose quantize value
                   CTRL-0 = Quant 0 (don't scroll, just edit)
                   CTRL-1 = Quant 1 (default)
                   CTRL-2 = Quant 2
                   CTRL-3 ....
                   ...
                   CTRL-9 = Quant 9


R/L-AMIGA F1 .............. Open MIDI Filter Window
R/L-AMIGA F2 .............. Open MIDI Sample Dump Window
R/L-AMIGA F3 .............. Open MIDI Channelscope Window
R/L-AMIGA F4 .............. Open MIDI Controlsources Display Window
R/L-AMIGA F5 .............. Open MIDI Sample Processor Window
R/L-AMIGA F6 .............. Open MIDI Score Display Window
R/L-AMIGA F7 .............. Open MIDI MIDI Activity Window
R/L-AMIGA F8 .............. Open MIDI Channel Stacker/Remapper Window


KEYPAD: Channel quick selection

PC-keyboard option disabled:

    (  )  /  *            Channels 1-4
    7  8  9  -            Channels 5-8
    4  5  6  +            Channels 9-12
    1  2  3  <Enter>      Channels 13-16

PC-keyboard option enabled (see @{" System prefs " link "sysprefs"} ):

    1 to 9                Channels 1-9
    Enter with 1 to 8     Channels 9-16



KEYPAD 0 .................. 1 Octave down (for Amiga keyboard notes)
KEYPAD . .................. 1 Octave up   (for Amiga keyboard notes)

CTRL-KEYPAD ............... Mute or Unmute the corresponding instrument
                            (same as the Enable-gadgets in channelscope)


DEL ....................... (PT) Edit-mode only: delete note or value

SHIFT-DEL ................. Edit-mode only: delete full event in a note-track
                            (velocity, note, poly-pressure)

ALT-DEL ................... Delete full event on all note-tracks in the 
                            current instrument. Editmode can be disabled.

BACKSPACE ................. (PT) Drag current event up one position. All
                            data following the current event is also dragged 
                            up a position. Edit-mode must be enabled.

SHIFT-BACKSPACE ........... Drag all events in the tracks up one position.
                            All data following the current event is also
                            dragged up a position. Please note that edit-mode 
                            does not have to be on!!

ALT-BACKSPACE ............. Same as SHIFT BACKSPACE but does all note
                            events for the entire pattern (all 16
			    instruments!)

RETURN .................... (PT) Insert event at current event-position. All 
                            following data is shifted down one.

SHIFT-RETURN .............. Insert event at current event-position for all
                            tracks in the current instrument. Editmode may
  			    be disabled.

ALT-RETURN ................ Same as SHIFT RETURN but shifts all note events
                            for the entire pattern (all 16 instruments!)

` (backwards-single-quote)  Edit-mode only: Put Note-OFF event into the 
                            current track.


HELP ...................... Show this documentation. Depending on the
                            currently active window, MidiTracker will load 
                            your desired link in this guide.



SEE ALSO  @{" Navigation keys " link "navigate"}

@Endnode
@Node "arexx" "ARexx Support!"

@{u}ARexx support@{uu}

The ARexx port's name is "rexx_MT". It can be altered at @{" System Preferences " link "sysprefs"}.

Supported commands are:


PLAYSONG          @{" Play song " link "playsong"} from current position.

PLAYPATT          @{" Play current pattern " link "playpatt"}.

STOP              @{" Stop " link "stopbutton"} playing or @{" recording " link "recording"}.

QUIT              Quit MidiTracker. Be careful! All song data will be
                  lost if not saved. (not yet implemented)

GETMODE           Places values into the @{i}result@{ui}-variable.
                    -2 = Playing song,
                    -1 = Playing pattern,
                     0 = Stopped,
                     1 = Recording pattern,
                     2 = Recording song,

@Endnode
@Node "recording" "Recording song data via MIDI"

@{u}Recording songs or patterns@{uu}

This section will explain a little on how to record midi data into a
pattern.

1. Select your preferred @{" record mode " link "recmode"}.
2. Hit the @{" Record Pattern " link "recpatt"} or @{" Record Song " link "recsong"} button in the main 
   window to start recording. MidiTracker will play back the song and store
   all incoming data into an internal record buffer.
3. Press @{" Stop " link "stopbutton"} to halt playback and recording. 
4. All recorded data is now inserted into the song.
5. Choose @{" Undo " link "undolastrecord"} from the main menu if you wish to restore the song to 
   its previous state.

If some of the tracks already contain note events before you record into
it, these tracks will not be overwritten (unless the 
@{" Cut channel before record " link "cutbeforerec"} option is turned on.) MidiTracker will record 
into the tracks beside the ones that currently contain data.

If the end of the song is reached and the recording goes on, new patterns
are added to the song automatically, increasing its length.

@Endnode
@Node "editing" "How to edit"

@{u}How to edit your song manually@{uu}

This section will explain a little about editing a pattern.

1. Select @{" editmode " link "editbutton"} from the main window. A blue cursor should appear 
   somewhere in the track display. 
2. Now you can enter controlsource data or midi notes either with your master 
   keyboard or with the Amiga keyboard. Incoming notes, controllers or
   program changes are put into the track where the cursor is, so if you
   want to insert Modwheel data into your pattern, place the cursor over
   the controlsource column and select "ModW" using the @{" Src " link "src"} gadget.
   Now move the master-keyboard's modwheel and MidiTracker should now
   insert your modwheel values into the controlsource track.

Entering notes with your synth is the easiest method of inputting note
events. You'll notice that MidiTracker also accepts Note-OFF events unless
the @{" Ignore Note-OFFs " link "ignorenoteoffs"} option is enabled. 

When in edit mode experiment with the quantize value and chord mode to see
how MidiTracker acts in edit mode.

@Endnode
@Node "mtplay" "The MTPlay tool"

@{u}MTPlay@{uu}

In the future when MidiTracker's @{" library " link "mtlib"} is complete, there will be
a MidiTracker player. It will be able to play MidiTracker-songs and may be
capable of some ARexx commands for transport control. This will allow you
to write scripts to play midi music in the background, for example.

@Endnode
@Node "mtlib" "MidiTracker library"

@{u}MidiTracker library@{uu}

Soon there will be a library with all the functions you need to load,
initialize, play, pause or stop a song. I hope I can do it in a way that
you can use it in demos and in system-friendly applications.

@Endnode
@Node "faq" "Frequently asked questions and answers"

@{u}Frequently asked questions@{uu}


@{u}Will MidiTracker ever support Amiga samples in tracks?@{uu}

No, not directly. In general MidiTracker is aimed at the professional
musician who uses pro midi gear. The Amiga's internal sound capabilities
are below the quality required for professional music (except for 3rd party
sound cards that very few people own.) Maybe in the future if we get a new
Power Amiga or new Amiga OS compatible computer, I will consider porting
MidiTracker and include internal sound support.

You CAN actually use samples with the help of a sample-player program;
look @{" here " link "usesamples"} for more info.


@{u}I've recorded in a part but some of the notes aren't there.@{uu}

Chances are you didn't have 'quantize record' activated and the notes are
there, you just have to zoom in the resolution to see them.


@{u}I want to see my synth in MidiTracker. How can I do that?@{uu}

See @{" Synth Support " link "synths"} for info on this topic.



This FAQ will grow in future, so feel free to ask questions about
MidiTracker.

@Endnode
@Node "playing" "Listen to your song"

@{u}Playing a song or a pattern@{uu}

There's nothing much to say about how to play a pattern or a song. Just
try it out and observe what happens :-)



SEE ALSO  @{" Play Song " link "playsong"} @{" Play Pattern " link "playpatt"}

